00:42:59.960 --> 00:43:01.150
JON BONNE: Yeah.

00:43:01.150 --> 00:43:04.610
LIV WU: So if you have
no more questions,

00:43:04.610 --> 00:43:07.764
I'm going to have you
describe the three

00:43:07.764 --> 00:43:09.055
wines that we have for tasting.

00:43:09.055 --> 00:43:09.721
JON BONNE: Sure.

00:43:09.721 --> 00:43:12.310
LIV WU: And then
we'll pour some wine.

00:43:12.310 --> 00:43:16.620
And then you can ask John more
questions while you're sipping.

00:43:16.620 --> 00:43:18.659
So talk about the
Chenin Blanc, first?

00:43:18.659 --> 00:43:19.950
JON BONNE: Yeah, it's in order.

00:43:19.950 --> 00:43:20.991
LIV WU: It'll be in here?

00:43:20.991 --> 00:43:21.870
Is it in there?

00:43:21.870 --> 00:43:22.590
Yes.

00:43:22.590 --> 00:43:24.420
JON BONNE: The Chenin Blanc.

00:43:24.420 --> 00:43:28.370
So we actually have two wines
from the same wine maker

00:43:28.370 --> 00:43:33.170
and then one from
another duo of guys.

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:35.780
So the Chenin Blanc is the
Leo Steen Chenin Blanc.

00:43:35.780 --> 00:43:38.910
It's made by a guy named Leo
Hansen, who's actually Danish.

00:43:38.910 --> 00:43:41.770
Was a sommelier, a very famous
sommelier in Copenhagen.

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:46.320
And wanted to make wine,
so he came to California.

00:43:46.320 --> 00:43:48.530
Makes wine actually for
a vineyard in Sonoma

00:43:48.530 --> 00:43:49.840
called Stuhlmuller.

00:43:49.840 --> 00:43:52.530
But also has his own
label called Leo Steen.

00:43:52.530 --> 00:43:54.220
Steen is his middle name.

00:43:54.220 --> 00:43:56.880
Steen is also the South African
name, the historical South

00:43:56.880 --> 00:43:58.670
African name, for
Chenin Blanc, which

00:43:58.670 --> 00:44:01.510
is the other place in the
world where it grows well.

00:44:01.510 --> 00:44:05.740
And this is his Chenin Blanc.

00:44:05.740 --> 00:44:09.520
It's from Dry Creek Valley,
from a vineyard called Saini,

00:44:09.520 --> 00:44:14.660
S-A-I-N-I. About 30-year-old
vines, dry farmed.

00:44:14.660 --> 00:44:17.970
And in fact, I think
all of the wines, today,

00:44:17.970 --> 00:44:19.800
are from dry-farmed vineyards.

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:22.350
In fact, from dry-farmed
organic vineyards.

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:24.270
So about 30 years old.

00:44:24.270 --> 00:44:27.705
Kind of a parcel that the farmer
forgot or was selling off.

00:44:27.705 --> 00:44:31.350
Because Chenin Blanc used to
be a very significant grape

00:44:31.350 --> 00:44:33.430
in California in
the '70s and '80s.

00:44:33.430 --> 00:44:37.850
And then got this reputation
for being kind of trashy and not

00:44:37.850 --> 00:44:40.450
that interesting.

00:44:40.450 --> 00:44:41.850
And people stopped drinking it.

00:44:41.850 --> 00:44:44.821
And so Leo and a
handful of other folks

00:44:44.821 --> 00:44:46.320
have started to
bring it back really

00:44:46.320 --> 00:44:50.720
as this great, sort of
aromatic, slightly spicy

00:44:50.720 --> 00:44:54.710
table wine, that is great.

00:44:54.710 --> 00:44:56.520
I don't tend to age
this wine very long,

00:44:56.520 --> 00:45:00.880
but I have friends who
do age it and insist,

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:03.726
among other things, that
the 2006 bottling of this

00:45:03.726 --> 00:45:05.600
is one of the best Chenin
Blancs they've had.

00:45:05.600 --> 00:45:07.780
And this is someone, by the way,
who makes, what I would argue,

00:45:07.780 --> 00:45:09.650
is the best Chenin
Blanc in California.

00:45:09.650 --> 00:45:13.990
So if he thinks Leo is beating
him, I'll give him that.

00:45:13.990 --> 00:45:16.940
LIV WU: And it's $16, $17?

00:45:16.940 --> 00:45:17.860
How much is that?

00:45:17.860 --> 00:45:20.950
JON BONNE: About
that. $17, yeah.

00:45:20.950 --> 00:45:24.430
Directly behind you-- and
I'm going in the order

00:45:24.430 --> 00:45:26.680
that I would
probably taste them--

00:45:26.680 --> 00:45:37.290
is the-- there we go-- the
Birichino 2012 Sinsault.

00:45:37.290 --> 00:45:39.920
So Birichino is a project
from two guys, John Locke

00:45:39.920 --> 00:45:41.695
and Alex Kraus.

00:45:41.695 --> 00:45:43.820
Both of them worked for
Randal Graham at Bonny Doon

00:45:43.820 --> 00:45:45.840
and survived.

00:45:45.840 --> 00:45:48.950
And John actually
still runs a wine shop

00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:52.130
in Santa Cruz called "Swap."

00:45:52.130 --> 00:45:54.720
So they make wine
together under this label.

00:45:54.720 --> 00:45:57.689
And this is from one of
my favorite vineyards

00:45:57.689 --> 00:45:58.230
in the state.

00:45:58.230 --> 00:46:00.980
It's from a vineyard
called Bechthold,

00:46:00.980 --> 00:46:03.860
which is in western Lodi.

00:46:03.860 --> 00:46:08.430
And it was planted
in 1886 to Sinsault,

00:46:08.430 --> 00:46:11.830
which is a not terribly
noteworthy grape

00:46:11.830 --> 00:46:14.170
from southern France.

00:46:14.170 --> 00:46:18.810
And somehow Bechthold has become
the darling of all California.

00:46:18.810 --> 00:46:22.390
Everyone wants to get into
Bechthold and make Sinsault.

00:46:22.390 --> 00:46:25.680
Turley, actually, was the
first big name to get in there

00:46:25.680 --> 00:46:27.810
and make this very
Beaujolais style.

00:46:27.810 --> 00:46:29.210
They now are in there.

00:46:29.210 --> 00:46:34.640
Randall used to use
it for Cigare Volante.

00:46:34.640 --> 00:46:38.770
And a handful of other folks,
Scholium Project, et cetera.

00:46:38.770 --> 00:46:42.740
Like I said, it's sort of
organically farmed, by neglect.

00:46:42.740 --> 00:46:44.650
Nobody ever bothered
to put chemicals on it.

00:46:44.650 --> 00:46:48.825
So and again, sort of
sandy soils, dry-farmed.

00:46:48.825 --> 00:46:50.700
And it's this completely
improbable vineyard.

00:46:50.700 --> 00:46:54.400
No one's entirely sure how
it survived, because nobody

00:46:54.400 --> 00:46:56.130
made any money in
Lodi selling grapes.

00:46:56.130 --> 00:46:58.840
And certainly not
low-yielding grapes--

00:46:58.840 --> 00:47:02.770
from low--yielding dry-farmed
vines that were getting,

00:47:02.770 --> 00:47:05.850
I don't know, $400 a ton and
are now getting like, maybe,

00:47:05.850 --> 00:47:07.840
three times that.

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:12.040
So to me, this is this
quintessence one of, really,

00:47:12.040 --> 00:47:14.891
the longitivity of
California, and how,

00:47:14.891 --> 00:47:16.390
for all of the
newness, there really

00:47:16.390 --> 00:47:19.430
is a great lineage
back to the past.

00:47:19.430 --> 00:47:22.850
And to these grapes that were
once really important, here,

00:47:22.850 --> 00:47:26.940
before market forces dictated
that Cabernet and Chardonnay

00:47:26.940 --> 00:47:29.410
would take over.

00:47:29.410 --> 00:47:32.980
And it's just pretty,
it's fragrant.

00:47:32.980 --> 00:47:34.800
It is-- to your
point, before-- it

00:47:34.800 --> 00:47:37.870
is a wine that I think would
go with quite a lot of food,

00:47:37.870 --> 00:47:39.710
because it's subtle.

00:47:39.710 --> 00:47:42.110
The tannins are very, very soft.

00:47:42.110 --> 00:47:45.110
It's not a tannic grape.

00:47:45.110 --> 00:47:46.690
And I think, more
than anything, it

00:47:46.690 --> 00:47:50.380
preserves this really
significant vineyard

00:47:50.380 --> 00:47:55.060
that is very much a
historical artifact.

00:47:55.060 --> 00:47:59.630
On similar lines, right around
the corner, back to Leo,

00:47:59.630 --> 00:48:04.110
is the-- here we go--
the Leo Steen Calpella.

00:48:04.110 --> 00:48:05.834
And this is--
unfortunately, I think

00:48:05.834 --> 00:48:07.750
he's going to move on
to a different vineyard.

00:48:07.750 --> 00:48:10.940
But so he also wanted
to make a red wine.

00:48:10.940 --> 00:48:14.070
Oh, and the Bechtold
is, I think, $19.

00:48:14.070 --> 00:48:16.110
$19 or $20.

00:48:16.110 --> 00:48:20.540
And so the Leo Steen Calpella
is a blend going back, again,

00:48:20.540 --> 00:48:23.730
to historically important
grapes in California.

00:48:23.730 --> 00:48:28.200
It's a blend of Carignan
and Petit Syrah.

00:48:28.200 --> 00:48:30.550
The vineyard's about
60, 65 years old.

00:48:30.550 --> 00:48:31.950
It's called the Testa Vineyard.

00:48:31.950 --> 00:48:34.750
It's in Calpella, which
is a tiny little hamlet

00:48:34.750 --> 00:48:38.680
in Mendocino, right off the 101.

00:48:38.680 --> 00:48:41.100
And again, this is
one of those vineyards

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:42.780
that just survived by neglect.

00:48:42.780 --> 00:48:45.880
It's dry-farmed,
organically farmed.

00:48:45.880 --> 00:48:47.957
Again, just old
Mendocino farming family,

00:48:47.957 --> 00:48:49.540
didn't really know
what to do with it.

00:48:49.540 --> 00:48:51.860
But didn't want to take
it out, so they've now

00:48:51.860 --> 00:48:55.550
found buyers who are interested
in paying them fair market

00:48:55.550 --> 00:48:57.300
value.

00:48:57.300 --> 00:48:59.340
So Carignan was the
great workhorse grape

00:48:59.340 --> 00:49:02.450
of the late 19th and
early 20th century.

00:49:02.450 --> 00:49:05.980
Planted all over a very big
part of the old field blends.

00:49:05.980 --> 00:49:07.360
Can make an
interesting wine when

00:49:07.360 --> 00:49:10.040
it's from old vines,
which this is.

00:49:10.040 --> 00:49:12.790
Got again a reputation
for being sort of lowly

00:49:12.790 --> 00:49:17.110
and uninteresting, which it can
be, if it's not farmed well.

00:49:17.110 --> 00:49:22.230
But makes this very savory,
spicy, complex wine.

00:49:22.230 --> 00:49:24.860
There's usually kind of a
celery seed component to it.

00:49:24.860 --> 00:49:27.290
Petit Syrah being the
other piece of the blending

00:49:27.290 --> 00:49:29.230
component, historically.

00:49:29.230 --> 00:49:29.950
Used for color.

00:49:29.950 --> 00:49:31.840
Used for tannin.

00:49:31.840 --> 00:49:33.740
Very tannic, very kind of blue.

00:49:33.740 --> 00:49:36.245
It's like blueberries
and sandpaper.

00:49:39.170 --> 00:49:41.500
It's not a huge
component in here.

00:49:41.500 --> 00:49:44.930
I think this is a very
appropriate use of it.

00:49:44.930 --> 00:49:47.430
But again, this notion, this
is obviously more structured.

00:49:47.430 --> 00:49:51.160
But if you think about what
a really good, somewhat

00:49:51.160 --> 00:49:53.550
savory table wine
should be, I think

00:49:53.550 --> 00:49:56.080
this is a perfect,
perfect example.

00:49:56.080 --> 00:50:00.250
And again, it's $18, maybe.

00:50:00.250 --> 00:50:00.900
LIV WU: Great.

00:50:00.900 --> 00:50:02.850
So look forward to tasting it.

00:50:02.850 --> 00:50:04.490
Thank you so much.

